// Canonical Sutra definitions for the Promise<T> API.
//
// Promises are first-class Sutra vocabulary, with a two-stage
// beta-reduction defined in planning/sutra-spec/promises.md:
//
//   async function     (sugar over)
//      ↓
//   Promise<T>         (sugar over)
//      ↓
//   while_loop with two-channel halt vector  (substrate primitive)
//
// This file declares the middle layer — the Promise<T> class that
// the async/await desugar pass (queue.md item 1, phase 3) lowers
// async functions INTO, and that the Promise→while_loop pass
// (phase 6) lowers OUT OF into substrate `while_loop` declarations.
//
// Today the intrinsic method bodies live in the runtime as
// commented-out future work — no `_VSA.promise_resolve(...)` /
// `_VSA.promise_reject(...)` exist yet. Calls to these methods
// parse and validate cleanly but error at runtime until phase 6
// implements the substrate backing. See the queue.md item 1
// phase plan for the order things land in.

// ==========================================================================
// Section 1 — implemented in pure Sutra
// ==========================================================================

// (Pending: `then` / `catch` / `all` / `race` need lambda / first-
// class-function support to express the callback parameter without
// hoisting. Per the 2026-05-08 TS transpiler note, arrow functions
// today get hoisted to top-level `function` declarations rather
// than passed as values; once values-of-function-type are real
// in Sutra, the body of `then(callback) -> Promise<U>` becomes
// expressible directly here as a single .su function whose body
// the inliner can substitute. Until then, the desugar pass
// (phase 3) generates explicit named functions for each .then()
// callback and threads them through manually.)


// ==========================================================================
// Section 2 — blocked on intrinsics (or substrate design)
// ==========================================================================

// then — chain a continuation. Returns a new Promise that resolves
// with the value the callback returns (or the value the callback's
// returned-promise resolves to, if the callback itself returns a
// Promise — chained promises auto-flatten).
//
//   function Promise then(Promise self, callback cb) {
//       // Wait for `self` to settle.
//       // If fulfilled, run cb(self.value()) and return its result.
//       // If rejected, propagate the rejection without running cb.
//       ...
//   }
//
// Blocked on: lambda / first-class function values, and on the
// Promise→while_loop substrate lowering (phase 6) that defines
// what "wait for self to settle" means at the substrate.


// catch — chain a rejection handler. Returns a new Promise that
// resolves with the value the handler returns; if the upstream
// promise was fulfilled, the handler doesn't run and the value
// passes through.
//
//   function Promise catch(Promise self, callback cb) { ... }
//
// Blocked on: same as then.


// all — wait for an array of promises to all settle. Returns a
// promise that resolves with the array of values when every input
// promise has fulfilled, or rejects with the first rejection.
//
//   function Promise all(Promise[] ps) { ... }
//
// Blocked on: array-of-promise typing, the substrate fan-in for
// multi-channel halt. Lowering: a single fused while_loop with one
// halt channel per input plus a global "all-done" channel.


// race — first-to-settle wins. Returns a promise that resolves with
// the value of whichever input promise settles first.
//
//   function Promise race(Promise[] ps) { ... }
//
// Blocked on: same as all, plus a "first-saturating" arbiter on
// the multi-channel halt.


class Promise extends vector {
    // Construct an already-fulfilled Promise wrapping `value`. No
    // loop cycling — the halt vector's `fulfilled` channel is
    // saturated at construction time. The substrate backing builds
    // the standard promise vector with the value on the resolved-
    // value axis and `fulfilled = 1`, `rejected = 0`.
    static intrinsic method Promise resolve(vector value);

    // Construct an already-rejected Promise wrapping `reason`. Mirror
    // of `resolve` on the rejected channel.
    static intrinsic method Promise reject(vector reason);

    // Inspect the three states. Each takes the Promise as first arg
    // (per the stdlib convention: instance methods are static funcs
    // with obj first arg). Each returns a fuzzy/bool reading of the
    // corresponding halt channel.
    static intrinsic method bool isFulfilled(Promise self);
    static intrinsic method bool isRejected(Promise self);
    static intrinsic method bool isPending(Promise self);

    // Read the resolved value (valid only when isFulfilled()) or the
    // rejection reason (valid only when isRejected()). Reading the
    // wrong one returns a noisy vector — the substrate doesn't gate
    // the read on the halt-channel state. Caller is responsible.
    static intrinsic method vector value(Promise self);
    static intrinsic method vector reason(Promise self);

    // Loop-bodied await — the substrate-level shape of `await p`.
    // Conceptually equivalent to:
    //     while_loop spin(Promise.isPending(p) > 0.5, slot p) {
    //         pass p;
    //     }
    //     return Promise.value(p);
    // i.e. a while_loop gating on `p`'s pending state, body just
    // re-passes the slot (no progress without external I/O), then
    // unwraps the resolved value once the loop exits.
    //
    // For Sutra programs without external I/O (current state), a
    // pending promise never changes mid-execution; an already-
    // resolved promise exits the loop in 0 iterations. When Yantra
    // wires up axon-IO writes, the producer side flips isPending
    // and the next iteration exits with the resolved value.
    //
    // The Stage-1 desugar pass emits `await x` as
    // `Promise.await_value(x)` rather than `Promise.value(x)`, so
    // the loop semantics are baked into the desugared form even
    // though today's runtime implementation collapses to immediate
    // unwrap. See planning/sutra-spec/promises.md §"Lowering" and
    // planning/sutra-spec/axon-io.md.
    static intrinsic method vector await_value(Promise self);
}
